Runs lifecycle phase 1 for ctx-cage: gates billed modes on a clean git tree, mints a per-run tempdir, and materializes the files bound into the cage sandbox. Its output (`Prep`) is torn down later by `teardown_run` (not in this file).

The core entry point is `prepare_run(r: &Resolved) -> Result<Prep, CageError>`. For billed modes (`mode_is_billed`), it calls `ensure_clean_tree` before doing anything else, and resolves a `ClaudeRuntime` via `resolve_claude_runtime`; non-billed modes skip both, leaving `Prep.claude` as `None`. `ensure_clean_tree` shells out to `git status --porcelain` in the target root — errors if the root isn't a git repo, and refuses a dirty tree unless `allow_dirty` is set. This exists because the cage mounts the workspace read-write, so git-commit is the only rollback path for billed runs; a dirty starting tree breaks that guarantee.

`mint_rundir` names the tempdir `ctxcage-<task_id>-<pid>` under `TMPDIR`, force-removing any stale dir of the same name first (pid reuse could in theory collide, though practically won't across pids). `write_rules_file` and `write_resolv_file` dump compile-time embedded constants (`CAGE_RULES_MD`, `CAGE_RESOLV_CONF`) into the rundir unmodified — keep those constants and this file's paths in sync with whatever mounts them into the container (elsewhere in the crate). `write_mask_file` creates an empty regular file (not `/dev/null`, which can't be bind-mounted due to `nodev`) used to mask secret paths.

All I/O failures surface as `CageError::Io`; git/config problems as `CageError::Protocol`.